The primary system components include:

? Two (2) High-Temperature Screw Compressors;
? Two (2) Low-Temperature Screw Compressors;
? Two (2) Evaporative Condensers;
? One (1) High-Pressure Receiver;
? One (1) High-Temperature Recirculator Package;
? One (1) Low-Temperature Recirculator Package;
? Four (4) Ammonia Pumps (two at each recirculator package); and
? Seventeen (17) Evaporators

Additional system components include:

? Oil Pots (one each at each liquid recirculator package for draining oil);
? Automatic Purger (with a foul gas tap at the evaporative condensers and a tap on the high pressure liquid line from the high pressure receiver and the liquid recirculation packages);
? One (1) Floor-Warming Heat Exchanger using glycol as the heat transfer fluid; and,
? Interconnecting Piping and Control Valves.

Safety systems include:

? Pressure relief valves on all pressure vessels in the system;
? Ammonia diffusion tank, 15,600 gallon capacity (all relief valve discharge lines lead to the diffusion tank for mixing with water in the event of a release from a component relief valve);
? Fire dump valve arrangement in ammonia diffusion panel for use by the fire department in the event of an emergency;
? Compressor safety cutouts and control panels to shut down the compressor operation if safe operating conditions are exceeded;
? Liquid level float switches;
? High level vessel alarms;
? Dual hot-gas solenoid valves;
? PLC alarm notification;
? Ventilation system for continuous and emergency ventilation;
? Emergency Control Station with emergency ventilation fan switch and emergency shutdown switch;
? Ammonia detection and alarm system for response to elevated

levels of ammonia vapor in the cooling, freezer, and storage areas.  Detection will trigger the emergency ventilation system, emergency shutdown, and audible/visual alarms at preset levels;
? Spring-loaded, self-closing oil drain valves;
? Manual stop valves;
? Manual and solenoid-controlled ¿King Valve¿ to stop liquid refrigerant flow from the high-pressure receiver;
? Physical barriers to protect equipment/piping from collisions (e.g. bollards);
? Fire sprinkler system;
? Fire extinguishers; and
? Emergency showers and eyewash stations
The extent of involvement in the operation of the refrigeration system by employees is limited to daily monitoring and recording.  The maintenance of the system will be contracted to a qualified refrigeration contractor.

The facility maintains an Emergency Action Plan for response to ammonia releases.  The Plan includes notification and evacuation protocols.

THE GENERAL ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION PROGRAM AND THE CHEMICAL SPECIFIC PREVENTION STEPS

This facility complies with the California Accidental Release Prevention (CalARP) Program and OSHA¿s Process Safety Management (PSM) Program.  Key prevention steps taken by this facility to maintain safety are outlined in the PSM Program.  These include the description of all system and equipment information, process hazard analysis, operator training, contractor qualification, operating procedures, pre-startup safety review, hot work permitting, management of change, mechanical integrity, incident investigation, compliance audits, and emergency response.

Those who operate, maintain, or supervise the system will be trained to understand the principles of ammonia refrigeration and ammonia properties, an understanding of the process equipment and proper operating and maintenance procedures, recognition of abnormal conditions and the steps to correct deviations, and emergency shutdown procedures as appropriate to the level of involvement each employee will have with the process.  Contr
